<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'EL CID' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Michael Wilmington 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This 1961 super spectacle about the man (Charlton Heston, pictured with Sophia 
Loren) who drove the Moors out of Spain is the kind of movie they don't make 
anymore: a vast pageant, loaded with decor and furious action. Romance, 
swashbuckling jousts, sword fights and grand battle scenes -- with 5,000 
soldiers of the Spanish army acting as extras in the climax -- combine for this 
historical extravaganza. Produced by Samuel Bronston, directed by Anthony Mann 
and written by Philip Yordan, Fredric M. Frank and the uncredited blacklist 
victim Ben Barzman, it paints a corrupt, obsessive Spanish court filled with 
cruel intrigue and perverse psychological (NBC Sunday at 7 p.m.). Michael 
Wilmington 
</P>
