<HEADLINE>
<P>
PROPOSITION 1A'S DEFEAT STILL PACKS A JOLT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Proposition 1A, which would have helped pay for earthquake-related repairs 
and the retrofitting of unsafe highway bridges and freeway arteries, was 
defeated for several reasons, none of which Paul Clarke mentions in his 
Commentary article of June 19. 
</P>
<P>
 He pins the blame on our neighboring counties. But most of the blame can be 
laid at the foot of Gov. Pete Wilson, who, shortly after the Jan. 17 
earthquake, did his imitation of former President George Bush by refusing to 
consider a temporary increase in the sales tax. This despite numerous public 
opinion polls detailing that a clear majority of Californians (in some cases 
over 60%) supported this avenue to pay for the quake, a la the Loma Prieta 
quake, and subsequent temporary sales tax increase to finance the repairs. 
</P>
<P>
 Moreover, Wilson did not campaign for Proposition 1A, even though he favored 
the bond method of payment and it was his idea in the first place. Without the 
effective stewardship of President Bill Clinton, we Californians would be up a 
creek without a paddle, and our vital freeways would not have been reopened so 
quickly. This is called leadership. 
</P>
<P>
 It is in the public interest to pay for the quake with a one-fourth-cent 
temporary increase in the sales tax. Yes, it is regressive, but a least the 
earthquake would be paid for in the next year or two. 
</P>
<P>
 Voters are not stupid, and they understand that the passage of bond measures 
to finance anything translates to paying more in the long run. It is like 
purchasing a $1,000 stereo with a credit card and taking many months to pay 
off; the $1,000 stereo becomes considerably more expensive. 
</P>
<P>
 Is this any way to pay for a natural disaster? Voters have said no. 
</P>
<P>
 Finally, Wilson had no contingency plan if the bond measure failed. Now, as 
the 1994-95 budget is moving through the Legislature, his own Finance 
Department has acknowledged making a $2.7-billion error in estimating cash 
flow, further complicating earthquake repair costs. In football, when a smart 
quarterback realizes the defense is prepared for the play called, he calls out 
an audible switch to another play. Gov. Wilson is the QB. Will he run, pass or 
punt? Or will he call an audible and show Californians in general, and 
Valleyites in particular, something he has not demonstrated -- leadership?  
</P>
<P>
 HOWARD COHEN 
</P>
<P>
 North Hills 
</P>
<P>
 * Despite Paul Clarke's analysis, the "no" vote on Proposition 1A had 
absolutely nothing to do with apathy or lack of community with our neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
 A "no" vote meant simply that we do not want another bad measure to add to our 
debt, for which our children and grandchildren will be accountable. Our 
children and grandchildren will have disasters of their own, worse ones than we 
experienced on Jan. 17, as Mr. Clarke himself acknowledges. We need to pay for 
the damages, yes, but we need to pay as we go, not put off until tomorrow, when 
we will have to pay for new damage created by new disasters. 
</P>
<P>
 I hope that the voters, like myself, who defeated Proposition 1A are willing 
to accept higher taxes to pay for the damage from the Northridge quake, because 
that is the message we sent on June 7. This is the message we should be sending 
to our state representatives, who would like nothing better than to defer such 
tough decisions to us and to generations yet unborn. 
</P>
<P>
 JOHN DeVINCENT 
</P>
<P>
 Glendale 
</P>
</TEXT>
