<HEADLINE>
<P>
SEASONAL FRUIT; WHERE TO PICK 'EM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This is but a sampling of Southland locations where you can pick your own 
fruits and vegetables. 
</P>
<P>
 Rick Brecunier has a 25-acre ranch to which most people come for the 
olallieberries, green beans, yellow wax beans, purple beans, squash, Royal 
apricots and cucumbers. 
</P>
<P>
 * Tierra Rejada Ranch, 3370 Moorpark Road, Moorpark. (805) 529-3690 . 
</P>
<P>
 At PJK Cherry Farm, Paul Kish has a 1,400-tree orchard, all Bings. 
</P>
<P>
 * PJK Cherry Farm, 145674 Copco Road, Gorman. (818) 337-6498 .  
</P>
<P>
 The peach season kicks off this weekend at Yingst Ranch, with Red Tops. It 
will run all summer long with Babcocks appearing around July 21. Charlie and 
Nancy Yingst also grow pears, which will come in around the beginning of 
August, and apples, which will be in a little later. 
</P>
<P>
 * Yingst Ranch, 35349 80th East, Littlerock. (805) 944-2425 . 
</P>
<P>
 Kenny and Toyoko Zink's early peaches, which will begin to be harvested this 
week, are Red Heavens. They also have Tilton apricots. Later in the summer 
they'll have Bartlett pears. 
</P>
<P>
 * Zink Ranch, 35609 80th East, Littlerock. (805) 944-1239.  
</P>
<P>
 The City of Los Angeles Parks and Recreation Department has a one-weekend 
picking of Valencia oranges and White Marsh grapefruit July 9 and 10 at 
city-owned Orcutt Ranch in West Hills. Picking runs 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. and the 
fruit costs $2 a shopping bag -- bring your own bag. 
</P>
<P>
 * Orcutt Ranch, 23600 Roscoe Blvd., West Hills. (818) 883-6641.  
</P>
<P>
 At Bill O'Leary's ranch in Wheeler Canyon, you can pick Royal apricots from 
trees planted by his father in 1903. They should be in within the next two 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
 * O'Leary Ranch, Wheeler Canyon, near Santa Paula. (805) 525-6358.  
</P>
<P>
 At Friend's Ranch fruit stand, they sell Valencia oranges and some navels, 
avocados, grapefruit, tomatoes and squash. 
</P>
<P>
 * Friend's Ranches, 15150 Maricopa Highway, Ojai. (805) 646-2871.  
</P>
<P>
 Dorothy Holmes runs a small farm stand near Wheeler Hot Springs in Ojai, 
selling unsprayed peaches by the lug. The Venturas will be in in a week, then 
Elbertas and Bonitas. Call first. 
</P>
<P>
 * Dorothy Holmes, 16350 Maricopa Highway, Ojai. (805) 646-1231.  
</P>
<P>
 This 7-year-old farm stand, located just off Santa Monica Road in Carpinteria, 
has olallieberries, boysenberries and raspberries. 
</P>
<P>
 * Foley's Berries, 3915 Foothill Road, Carpinteria. (805) 684-1912 . 
</P>
