<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY; PRESERVATION: 2 AWARDS GO TO CULVER CITY PROJECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The restored Ivy Substation in Culver City has won awards from two major 
preservation organizations. 
</P>
<P>
 The substation, which once distributed electrical power for local rail 
service, won the Los Angeles Conservancy's 1994 Conservancy Preservation Award. 
It was cited for "exemplary completed rehabilitation" in this year's awards 
presentation by the City of Los Angeles' Cultural Heritage Commission. 
</P>
<P>
 Built in 1907, the Ivy Substation is the only remaining unaltered substation 
built by the Los Angeles Pacific Co. Renovated at a cost of $2 million for the 
Culver City Redevelopment Agency, it now serves as a community center and 
houses a community theater. The restoration project was managed by Tishman 
Construction Corp. 
</P>
