<HEADLINE>
<P>
TALES FROM TRUCKEE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Dianne Klein obviously feels a fondness for Truckee that I don't. ("Truckee 
Stop," May 15). I drove into Truckee last winter just as a snowstorm 
hit.Instead of risking the drive up a steep hill in the snow with my wife and 
2-year-old daughter in the car, I parked in the Safeway lot and asked the 
people we came to visit to pick us up in their four-wheel-drive vehicle. 
Despite our friend's assurance that the lot was a safe place to park for the 
night, I wasn't terribly surprised to return the next morning to find the car 
had been towed. I was disgusted to learn, however, that the ransom to retrieve 
my car after a tow of less than a mile was $230! There is a difference between 
depending on tourists for income and preying on them. Truckee, at least in this 
instance, clearly sanctions the latter. 
</P>
<P>
 JOHN HENNESSY 
</P>
<P>
 Mar Vista 
</P>
