<P>
S. KOREANS MARK WAR'S ANNIVERSARY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 South Korea marked the 44th anniversary Saturday of the outbreak of the Korean 
War with low-key public ceremonies but mounting backstage activity aimed at 
breaking half a century of bitter national division. 
</P>
<P>
 Veterans gathered at Seoul's National Cemetery to honor the millions killed in 
the 1950-53 conflict, which confirmed the post-World War II division of the 
peninsula into capitalist South and Communist North. 
</P>
<P>
 Thousands attended a rally in the capital's Olympic Park calling for peaceful 
unification of the two Koreas. 
</P>
<P>
 This year's anniversary comes at a time of mounting hopes that faltering steps 
toward reconciliation might this time produce results. 
</P>
<P>
 North Korea on Saturday notified the South of the names of a high-powered 
delegation that will meet Seoul officials Tuesday in a bid to arrange a 
historic summit meeting between the presidents of the two Koreas. 
</P>
